inciples Maria Theresa lived by, and she demanded the same from her family, her court, and her subjects.A panoramic work of scholarship that brings Europe's age of empire spectacularly to life, Maria Theresa paints an unforgettable portrait of the uncompromising yet singularly charismatic woman who left her enduring mark on the era in which she lived and reigned.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 7aHISTORY / Europe / Austria & Hungary.2bisacsh  aAdviser.  aAnschluss.  aApathy.  aArchduke.  aAristocracy.  aAulic Council.  aCabinet noir.  aCensorship.  aCivilian.  aClementia.  aConsummation.  aCourt painter.  aCourtesy.  aCourtier.  aCriticism.  aDeportation.  aDespotism.  aDissolution of the Monasteries.  aDistrust.  aEdict of toleration.  aEdict.  aEducation.  aEgocentrism.  aElector of Mainz.  aElectorate of Saxony.  aExcommunication.  aFlattery.  aFoot the bill.  aFormality.  aGiacomo Casanova.  aGod.  aGodparent.  aGrandee.  aGreat power.  aHeresy.  aHofburg Palace.  aHoly Roman Empire.  aHouse of Bourbon.  aHouse of Habsburg.  aHouse of Wittelsbach.  aHypocrisy.  aImperial Diet (Holy Roman Empire).  aImperial State.  aImperial Throne (micronation).  aImpossibility.  aInfanticide.  aJansenism.  aJohann Jakob Moser.  aJohann Joseph Gassner.  aKing of the Romans.  aLandgrave.  aLimbo.  aLord High Steward.  aLouis Philippe I.  aMadame de Pompadour.  aMajesty.  aMaria Amalia of Saxony.  aMaria Carolina of Austria.  aMartin van Meytens.  aMessalina.  aMilitary Frontier.  aMilitary Order of Maria Theresa.  aMirrors for princes.  aMortal Fear (novel).  aMourning.  aNarcissism.  aNecromancy.  aNobility.  aOppression.  aPartitions of Poland.  aPeasant.  aPerfidious Albion.  aPersecutio